  "en_snotes_yusuf": "The Makkan valley is enclosed by hills on all sides, unlike Madinah, which has level cultivated plains. But just because of its natural isolation, it is fitted to be a centre for prayer and praise. Cf. 2:126, and n. 128. (The \"Fruits\" are there explained). The righteous, though they have to have sustenance, both in a literal and figurative sense, require also the love and sympathy of their fellow-men.",
  "en_snotes_asad": "I.e., the narrow desert valley of Mecca, which is enclosed by barren, rocky hills. By \"some of my offspring\" Abraham refers to Ishmael and his descendants who settled at Mecca. I.e., to be desirous of visiting them - namely, on pilgrimage to Mecca - and thus help them to maintain themselves in the holy but barren land. The phrase af idah min an-nas lends itself also to the rendering \"the hearts of some people\", in which case it could be taken to mean \"the hearts of the believers\" (Baghawi, Razi, Ibn Kathir).",
